{
  "doc_id": "57378",
  "text": "Accumulating evidence that tetraspanins such as CD81 have growth-promoting activity in certain human cancers has led to their emergence as potential therapeutic targets [CITATION_1] . Indeed, monoclonal antibodies directed at the tetraspanin26/CD37 have moved into phase 1 or phase 2 clinical trials for the treatment of chronic lymphocytic leukemia and nonHodgkin lymphoma [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The unexpected discovery of the intramembrane ligand-binding pocket represents a potential targetable site for modulating tetraspanin function using small molecules and provides a route forward for elucidation of the molecular mechanism of action of this enigmatic class of important but poorly understood proteins.",
